se genres as Haitian jazz, troubadour traditions, Vodou-jazz, konpa, mini-djaz, new generation, and roots music. He examines the complex interaction of music with power in contexts such as honorific rituals, sponsored street celebrations, Carnival, and social movements that span the political spectrum. With firsthand accounts by musicians, photos, song texts, and ethnographic descriptions, this book explores the profound manifestations of power and song in the day-to-day efforts of ordinary Haitians to rise above political repression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPopular musiczHaitiy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPower (Social sciences)zHaitixHistoryy20th century. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  ahaiti, haitian, music, popular, power, history, 20th century, oppression, colonialism, colonial, dictators, government, governing, resistance, postcolonial, postcolonialism, cultural studies, culture, politics, political, jazz, troubadour, traditions, voodoo, vodou, konpa, roots, mini-djaz, rituals, street celebrations, carnival, social movement, ethnography, photography, musicians, criticism, authenticity, baby doc duvalier, dechoukaj.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226032931423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226032931/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles